<subSubSection pageId="1" pageNumber="404" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="1.[151,1436,1529,1698]" pageId="1" pageNumber="404">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,266,1529,1554]" pageId="1" pageNumber="404">Diagnosis</emphasis>
. Antennae with minute apical stylus (
<figureCitation box="[693,823,1529,1554]" captionStart="FIGURES 12 – 19" captionStartId="6.[151,263,1952,1975]" captionTargetBox="[222,1363,198,1919]" captionTargetId="figure@6.[216,1371,193,1932]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="FIGURES 12 – 19. Amydrostylus triadicophallus gen. nov. et sp. nov., female paratype, SEM. 12, head lateral view; 13, head frontal view; 14, chaetotaxy of area around scape; 15, ocellar tubercle; 16, first flagellomere, with sensorial pits; 17, second flagellomere; 18 – 19, second flagellomere, detail of the minute stylus." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/253462/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="404">
Figs 
<number box="[751,823,1530,1554]" pageId="1" pageNumber="404" value="18.0" valueMax="19.0" valueMin="17.0">17–19</number>
</figureCitation>
), vein Sc ending in C, and br same length as bm (Figs 
<number box="[151,196,1565,1590]" pageId="1" pageNumber="404" value="6.5" valueMax="7.0" valueMin="6.0">6–7</number>
). Male genitalia well developed, 
<number box="[569,581,1566,1590]" pageId="1" pageNumber="404" value="3.0">3</number>
/ 
<number box="[590,604,1566,1590]" pageId="1" pageNumber="404" value="4.0">4</number>
abdomen length (
<figureCitation box="[806,893,1565,1590]" captionStart="FIGURES 10 – 11" captionStartId="5.[151,263,1952,1975]" captionTargetBox="[215,1379,202,1920]" captionTargetId="figure@5.[201,1386,193,1932]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURES 10 – 11. Amydrostylus triadicophallus gen. nov. et sp. nov. 10, male habitus (holotype); 11, female habitus (paratype). Scale bar: 1 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/253461/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="404">Figs 10</figureCitation>
, 20, 
<number box="[947,1021,1565,1590]" pageId="1" pageNumber="404" value="32.0" valueMax="35.0" valueMin="29.0">29–35</number>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="1" pageNumber="404" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="1.[151,1436,1529,1698]" pageId="1" pageNumber="404">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,326,1601,1626]" pageId="1" pageNumber="404">Etymology</emphasis>
. The generic epithet derives from the Greek 
<emphasis box="[839,934,1601,1625]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="404">amydros</emphasis>
, meaning indistinct, and 
<emphasis box="[1223,1287,1601,1625]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="404">stylus</emphasis>
, in reference to the tiny apical stylus of antenna of the species. The specific epithet derives from the Greek roots 
<emphasis box="[1329,1429,1637,1661]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="404">triadikos</emphasis>
, meaning triple, and 
<emphasis box="[375,458,1673,1697]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="404">phallus</emphasis>
, in allusion to the trifid aedeagus of this species.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
